info.description: Small, socketed spear head, the socket being hollow to a distance of 4 1/2" from haft end, and continued as a solid rib along the remainder of the blade. There are side loops about 1 1/8" from haft end, but the holes of these loops now blocked with, hard rusty, incrustation, which also occurs in patches on one face of the blade, and just inside the socket. The sides of the socket below the blade have been slightly flattened by filing - the marks of which show clearly. The base of the socket is slightly indented all round. Edges of blade badly chipped and blade also slightly cracked.

info.description: Edges and point fairly sharp; midrib extending to point, and angular in section; rib extends on each wing, parallel to the edge and curves in near the haft to join the loops; both loops are diamond-shaped, one of them being slightly broken. Orifices of socket partly missing; stump of wooden shaft remains in socket. There is a crack across the part where the socket meets the blade and the spearhead is slightly bent at this point.[;]Decoration: lines of parallel dots at intervals of about 1 mm. along each side of apex of midrib and base of midrib on both sides of the blade. Socket has incised lines near its mouth, and 8mm further up are 6 more incised lines. From the last if new incised lines, springs a chevron pattern, which goes round the whole circumference of the socket, the chevrons being filled with hatched lines. Compare spearhead III + from Bambridge N.R. Yorks, for similar ornament.

info.description: Long, socketed spear head, the socket being hollow to a distance of 153 mm [6 5/8"] from the shaft end, and continued as a solid rib to point.  Two loop holles at base of blade.  Slight chamfer along both edges, extending from the flattened end of the loop holes to the point.  One edge is badly damaged and the spear head has been broken across its width 133 mm [5 1/4"] from the point.  There is a small hole near the central rib; the end of the socket is almost completely broken away leaving only 12.5 mm [1/2"] of the edge.  Small fragments of wood inside socket.

info.description: Badly damaged. Very thin metal. Socket about 1/4mm thick. 2 Rivet holes. Mr. Pritchard writes to L.F. Chitty 31.10.23: "The 3 broken spearheads (bronze) were found in 1835 during excavations in connection with drainage of Willow Moor Farm. Of course the finder is dead, also his son who kept them in memory of his father; I knew the son casually but can not find out his name. I have no reason to doubt the authenticity of the specimens. Along with the bronze spearheads was found a stone celt (Knife LFC) also in my possession."
info.associations: Part of a hoard
info.publications: As. Wrekin Tenement 1834, T.F. Dukes, Nov. 20, 1834, in Arch XXVI, 464-5.[;]Brief mentions in Arch. Camb. III (4th S), 338, + Montgom. Collection III, 437[;]As "Willow Morr. Willow Farm, or Wrekin Farm, 1835", Hartshorne, Salopia Antiqua (1841); Arch Jour. VIII (1851) 197.; Shrops. Arch. Trans. IV (2) 279. "Wrekin Farm" but pp. 89-98 + plate quoting Evans "Wrekin Tenement", as "Near Little Wenlock" or "Little Wenlock, Stop" (error amended later). Evans B. Imps (Hoard No. 44) pp. 44, 113, 234, 314, 336, 452, 461, 465. He recognised that this was "possibly the same hoard as No. 41 (Wrekin Tenement)". That these two hoards are identical is proved by the same spearhead with limited openings + socketed celt with a notch chipped in the edge, or curving in each.  Anden, Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops. I, 203.
